---
import LightLayout from '../layouts/LightLayout.astro';
---

<LightLayout title="ACAS Cheatsheet — Raquel" description="Lo que ACAS te pide preparar + guion para la primera llamada. Referencia R194247/26.">

  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pt-12 md:pt-20 pb-6">
    <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
      <span class="text-5xl">📞</span>
      <div>
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 flex-wrap">
          <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">ACAS Cheatsheet</h1>
          <span class="px-3 py-1 rounded-full text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wider" style="background: var(--color-primary-soft); color: var(--color-primary);">R194247/26</span>
        </div>
        <p class="font-medium mt-1" style="color: var(--color-primary);">Para Raquel · preparación + primera llamada</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-xl p-5 mb-6" style="background: #fef3c7; border: 1px solid #fcd34d;">
      <p class="font-bold mb-2" style="color: #92400e;">🎯 Regla de oro</p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: #78350f;">
        Esta llamada <strong>no es una negociación</strong>. Es solo una introducción donde el conciliator se presenta y empieza a entender tu caso. <strong>No tienes que aceptar nada</strong>, ni rebajar tu cifra, ni comprometerte a nada. Si te presionan, di: <em>"I'd prefer to think about it and come back to you in writing."</em>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-xl p-5 mb-6" style="background: #ecfdf5; border: 1px solid #a7f3d0;">
      <p class="font-bold mb-2" style="color: #065f46;">📋 Lo que ACAS te pide preparar</p>
      <p class="text-sm mb-2" style="color: #064e3b;">Según la página oficial de ACAS, lo que necesitas tener listo es:</p>
      <ol class="text-sm space-y-1 ml-4" style="color: #064e3b;">
        <li><strong>1.</strong> Un resumen del caso con fechas.</li>
        <li><strong>2.</strong> Cuánto dinero crees que te deben.</li>
        <li><strong>3.</strong> Cuánto tiempo llevabas en M&S.</li>
        <li><strong>4.</strong> Las razones que te dio M&S para sus decisiones.</li>
        <li><strong>5.</strong> Qué hiciste para intentar resolver el problema antes de venir a ACAS.</li>
        <li><strong>6.</strong> Datos de contacto de M&S (incluido email).</li>
        <li><strong>7.</strong> Documentos de soporte (los pedirán cuando hagan falta).</li>
      </ol>
      <p class="text-sm mt-3" style="color: #064e3b;"><strong>Las secciones de abajo cubren cada uno de estos puntos en orden.</strong> Puedes leer la sección 1 directamente al conciliator, o copiar/pegar y enviárselo por email si te lo pide.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!-- 1. CASE SUMMARY (read/copy to email)                          -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-6">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">1 · Tu resumen del caso</h2>
    <p class="text-sm mb-4" style="color: var(--color-stone);">
      Esto es para leer al conciliator si te pregunta "<em>can you tell me what happened?</em>", o para copiar y enviar por email si te lo pide. <strong>Escrito en inglés, listo para usar.</strong>
    </p>

    <div class="rounded-xl p-5" style="background: var(--color-cloud); border: 1px solid var(--color-stone-soft);">
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        I worked at Marks &amp; Spencer for thirteen years, from May 2013 until 3 May 2026, based at the Maidenhead store. My role was Stylist, later treated by M&amp;S as Visual Merchandiser, although I never signed any change of contract.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        For more than three years I worked Monday to Friday with no weekend work. On 9 and 13 April 2026 my line manager Mahnoor Khan told me, in two meetings, that I would have to start working at least one weekend day every two weeks. The reasons M&amp;S gave were "operational requirements" and "the M&amp;S Way". No agreement was reached.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        Beyond the two formal meetings, Mahnoor approached me repeatedly outside any scheduled meeting during this period. She would come into the Visual Merchandising Office, or stop me on the shop floor while I was working, or catch me just before my lunch break, asking if I had "found a solution" or wanted to "have a quick chat". On at least one occasion the purpose of one of these unscheduled approaches was to warn me that she would be sending me the letter of enforcement that day or the following day. These approaches were framed as informal but were in substance further meetings about the same issue.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        On several occasions I told Mahnoor directly that I was struggling and asked whether we could schedule any further discussions on agreed days, because not knowing when the next conversation would happen was making my working day very difficult. The unscheduled approaches continued regardless. I began to actively avoid being in predictable locations at work.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        I was also told that Mahnoor would be going on holiday for two weeks shortly afterwards and would pass my case to another manager during that time. Knowing that I would potentially have to start the conversation again with a different manager who did not know me added significantly to the pressure I was under.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        The justification M&amp;S gave does not match how the role has actually operated. For more than two years before my resignation I was the only Visual Merchandiser in the store, working Monday to Friday with no weekend cover, and the store ran normally. From an operational point of view, visual merchandising work cannot effectively be done on weekends, because that is when customer footfall is highest and the store needs to focus on sales rather than on moving stock and displays around the shop floor. I was also never trained on tills, so it is unclear what work I could have done on weekends in any event.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        On 16 April I sent Mahnoor a <strong>Statutory Flexible Working Request</strong> under the Employment Relations (Flexible Working) Act 2023, asking to keep my Monday to Friday pattern. My family arrangement is that I dedicate weekends to my two young children. Working at weekends would mean missing the only time of the week when I can be fully present for them, which is when both my partner and I are available as a family. I do not have alternative childcare arrangements in place that would replicate that, nor would they substitute for direct parental time. I had also raised the same childcare context verbally with Mahnoor during both of our meetings on 9 and 13 April. Around the same time, I sent a second formal email rejecting the contractual change itself. M&amp;S have not given me a substantive decision on the Flexible Working Request within the two-month statutory time frame.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        On 17 April, Mahnoor sent me a "letter of enforcement" by email to my work account, giving me four weeks' notice to comply with the new weekend working pattern and stating that failure to comply would result in disciplinary action and ultimately dismissal. The same day, Mahnoor also refused a one-day holiday request for 22 April, citing "insufficient notice". This was the first refusal of holiday in my thirteen years at M&amp;S, and it came shortly after I had submitted the Flexible Working Request.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        When I made the holiday request I told Mahnoor only that the reason was personal. Her response, sent by Microsoft Teams, was in substance that she "understood I had a lot of personal matters to attend to, but that I should manage them in my own time". She did not ask what the personal matter was.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        By Sunday 19 April my anxiety had escalated significantly because of the cumulative pressure of the previous weeks. On Monday 20 April I felt unwell enough to call my GP, Dr Mehreen Khan at Claremont Surgery, who signed me off with work-related anxiety. The GP offered me two or three weeks signed off, but I asked for only one week because I wanted to return to work as soon as possible. My colleague, the other Visual Merchandiser at the store, had been off work for around a month and was due back the week I returned. I felt responsible for getting her up to speed on what had happened in her absence and I did not want her to come back to additional pressure on top of her own return to work.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        That same evening, the store manager Kyle called me at home during my medical leave. He suggested I might not be paid, asked me to keep Teams active, requested check-ins every 48 hours, asked when I had called the GP, and said Company Sick Pay would likely be suspended on the basis of section 7 of the Sickness Absence Policy because they considered me to be absent due to "a formal investigation or procedure". I asked him to stop the call; he continued citing "duty of care". M&amp;S have not provided me with the policy despite my request, and have not confirmed what formal procedure they were referring to.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        When my one-week fit note ended and I returned to work on Monday 27 April, the situation had not changed and it became clear to me that I could not continue. I submitted my resignation that same day, citing constructive dismissal. My letter referenced the unilateral contractual change, the holiday refusal, the conduct during my medical leave, the threat to suspend Company Sick Pay, and the impact on my health.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        On 28 April my representative sent M&amp;S a without prejudice settlement proposal of £35,000 plus notice pay, contribution to legal fees, an agreed reference, mutual confidentiality and no admission of liability. That remains my current settlement proposal.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        On 11 May, Josie Wolski from M&amp;S in-house legal responded refusing the proposal and offering to proceed via ACAS Early Conciliation. We opened Early Conciliation on 17 May. My claims are: constructive unfair dismissal, indirect sex discrimination, detriment for asserting a statutory right, and victimisation following a protected act.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!-- 2. LIST OF EVENTS WITH DATES                                  -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-6">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">2 · Lista de eventos con fechas</h2>
    <p class="text-sm mb-4" style="color: var(--color-stone);">
      <strong>Memorízate los 5 hitos clave de la caja morada.</strong> El timeline detallado es backup, por si te pregunta algo concreto.
    </p>

    <div class="rounded-xl p-5 mb-5" style="background: #f5f3ff; border: 1px solid #ddd6fe;">
      <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-3" style="color: #5b21b6;">📌 Los 5 hitos que tienes que saber de memoria</p>
      <ol class="text-sm space-y-2" style="color: #4c1d95;">
        <li><strong>1. 9 &amp; 13 April 2026 — Two meetings with my line manager Mahnoor Khan.</strong> M&amp;S told me I had to start working weekends, at least one Saturday or Sunday every two weeks, after more than three years of working Monday to Friday. No agreement was reached.</li>
        <li><strong>2. 16 April — Statutory Flexible Working Request</strong> emailed to Mahnoor, setting out in writing my childcare responsibilities and the family arrangement for weekends. Around the same time, a separate email rejecting the contractual change itself.</li>
        <li><strong>3. 17 April — Three things happened.</strong> (a) Mahnoor emailed me a <strong>"letter of enforcement"</strong> giving me four weeks to comply with the weekend pattern or face disciplinary action and ultimately dismissal. (b) Same day, Mahnoor refused a one-day holiday request for 22 April, citing "insufficient notice". First refusal of holiday in thirteen years. (c) Mahnoor's Teams reply said in substance that I should <em>"manage personal matters in my own time"</em>, without asking what the matter was.</li>
        <li><strong>4. 20 April — I was signed off by my GP with work-related anxiety.</strong> The GP offered two or three weeks but I asked for only one because I wanted to return as soon as possible. The same evening, the store manager Kyle called me at home during my medical leave, suggested "no pay", asked me to keep Teams active, did check-ins every 48 hours, and threatened to suspend Company Sick Pay invoking section 7 of the Sickness Absence Policy.</li>
        <li><strong>5. 27 April — I returned from sick leave and resigned that same day</strong>, citing constructive dismissal. The situation had not changed. <strong>28 April</strong> a without prejudice proposal of £35,000 was sent. <strong>11 May</strong> M&amp;S responded refusing the proposal. <strong>17 May</strong> we opened ACAS Early Conciliation.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <details class="rounded-lg p-4" style="background: var(--color-cloud);">
      <summary class="font-bold text-sm cursor-pointer" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">📜 Timeline detallado (despliega para consultar)</summary>
      <div class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-stone);">

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">Background (2013-2025)</p>
          <ul class="ml-4 mt-1 space-y-1">
            <li>• <strong>May 2013:</strong> joined M&amp;S Maidenhead as Stylist.</li>
            <li>• <strong>~2021:</strong> M&amp;S said they had lost my contract, offered a new one changing my job title to Visual Merchandiser. I refused to sign. They gave me a pay rise saying acceptance implied the change. I never signed.</li>
            <li>• <strong>~2022-2023:</strong> I worked as the only VM in the store, Monday to Friday, with no weekend cover.</li>
            <li>• <strong>~2024-2025:</strong> a second VM joined to cover alternate weekends. I continued Monday to Friday.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">9 April 2026 — first meeting with Mahnoor Khan</p>
          <p class="ml-4">M&amp;S communicated I had to start working at least one weekend day every two weeks, citing "operational requirements" and "the M&amp;S Way". I raised my childcare responsibilities and explained that weekends are the time I dedicate to my two young children as the primary carer, with no alternative childcare arrangements in place that would substitute for direct parental time. No agreement was reached.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">13 April 2026 — second meeting with Mahnoor Khan</p>
          <p class="ml-4">Still no agreement. Mahnoor said the next step would be a "letter of enforcement" with four weeks' notice.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">16 April 2026 — Statutory Flexible Working Request + rejection email</p>
          <p class="ml-4">(1) "Statutory Flexible Working Request" under the Employment Relations (Flexible Working) Act 2023, emailed to Mahnoor on 16 April, asking to keep the Monday to Friday pattern. The reason given in writing: childcare responsibilities for two young children on weekends, with no alternative childcare arrangements in place. (2) Around the same time, "Response to Proposed Changes to Working Pattern" email rejecting the contractual change, referencing Section 4 ERA 1996 and implied contractual term.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">17 April 2026 — letter of enforcement + holiday refused + Teams reply</p>
          <p class="ml-4">
            <strong>Letter of enforcement:</strong> Mahnoor sent me a formal email to my work email account titled "letter of enforcement", giving me four weeks' notice to comply with the new weekend working pattern. The email stated that failure to comply would lead to disciplinary action and ultimately dismissal. I no longer have access to my work email, but M&amp;S have the email on their systems.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Holiday refused:</strong> Same day, I requested one day off for 22 April for personal reasons. Mahnoor refused, citing "insufficient notice". First refusal in thirteen years. The flexible working request was a protected act, this refusal followed it.<br/><br/>
            <strong>Teams reply about "personal time":</strong> Mahnoor's reply, sent by Microsoft Teams, was in substance that she "understood I had a lot of personal matters to attend to, but that I should manage them in my own time". She did not ask what the personal matter was. M&amp;S have the Teams log on their systems; I no longer have access.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">20 April 2026 — GP fit note + Kyle's call</p>
          <p class="ml-4">Morning: GP Dr Mehreen Khan at Claremont Surgery signed me off with "anxiety", not fit for work, 20-27 April. The GP offered me two or three weeks signed off but I asked for only one week, because I wanted to return as soon as possible. <br/>
          Evening (17:28): Kyle (store manager) called me during the medical leave. He suggested "no pay", asked me to keep Teams active, requested check-ins every 48 hours, asked when I had called the GP. He invoked section 7 of the Sickness Absence Policy and said Company Sick Pay would likely be suspended because they considered me to be absent due to "a formal investigation or procedure". I asked him to stop the call. He continued citing "duty of care".</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">21 April 2026 — response to Kyle</p>
          <p class="ml-4">I sent a formal email to Kyle setting out: the cause of my anxiety, my symptoms, my request that contact be limited to flexible working and the policy clarification, and five direct questions about the CSP suspension threat.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">27 April 2026 — return from leave and resignation (same day)</p>
          <p class="ml-4">I returned to work on Monday 27 April after my one-week fit note ended. The situation had not changed. The same day, I resigned citing constructive dismissal. The letter referenced: unilateral contractual change, refusal of holiday after a protected act, conduct during medical leave, the CSP threat invoking a procedure M&amp;S never produced, and impact on my health.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">28 April 2026 — without prejudice proposal sent</p>
          <p class="ml-4">A without prejudice settlement proposal was sent to M&amp;S: £35,000 plus notice pay, contribution to legal fees, agreed reference, mutual confidentiality, no admission of liability.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">3 May 2026 — effective date of termination</p>
          <p class="ml-4">End of employment with M&amp;S.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">11 May 2026 — M&amp;S response</p>
          <p class="ml-4">Josie Wolski (M&amp;S in-house legal) responded refusing the proposal and offering ACAS Early Conciliation. No counter-offer.</p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <p class="font-bold" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">17 May 2026 — ACAS Early Conciliation opened</p>
          <p class="ml-4">I submitted the ACAS EC form online. Reference R194247/26. This is Day A.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </details>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!-- 3. HOW MUCH MONEY                                             -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-6">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">3 · Cuánto dinero reclamas</h2>

    <div class="rounded-lg p-4 mb-4" style="background: var(--color-cloud);">
      <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">📌 La frase base (si te pregunta tu cifra)</p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        <em>"A without prejudice settlement proposal of £35,000 was sent to M&amp;S on 28 April. That remains my current settlement proposal. It includes notice pay, a contribution to legal fees, an agreed reference, mutual confidentiality and no admission of liability."</em>
      </p>
      <p class="text-xs mt-3" style="color: var(--color-stone);">
        Esa cifra ya está en el expediente de M&amp;S, no es información nueva. <strong>No inventes una cifra nueva</strong>, ni la rebajes por iniciativa propia.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-lg p-4 mb-4" style="background: #f5f3ff; border: 1px solid #ddd6fe;">
      <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: #5b21b6;">📌 Si te pregunta "<em>how did you arrive at that figure?</em>"</p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed mb-2" style="color: #4c1d95;">
        Estructura de tres patas, sin números desglosados:
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed italic" style="color: #4c1d95;">
        "It reflects three things: the loss of a thirteen-year career and the time it takes to rebuild that, the impact on my health, which is documented in a GP fit note, and the way I was treated after raising a flexible working request, which I'm advised raises discrimination and victimisation concerns. The detailed breakdown is something I'd rather discuss in writing with my representative."
      </p>
      <p class="text-xs mt-3" style="color: #5b21b6;">
        <strong>Por qué funciona:</strong> tres patas dan estructura sin pedantería, "<em>I'm advised</em>" implica asesoramiento sin tener que aclarar quién, y cierras devolviendo a escrito.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-lg p-4 mb-4" style="background: #fffbeb; border: 1px solid #fde68a;">
      <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: #92400e;">📌 Si insiste "<em>can you give me a sense of how it breaks down?</em>"</p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed italic" style="color: #78350f;">
        "It includes loss of earnings, the impact of what happened, and the legal claims I'd otherwise be pursuing. I'd rather not get into specific figures by component on this call, those are best handled in writing."
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="background: #fef2f2; border: 1px solid #fecaca;">
      <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-2" style="color: #991b1b;">📌 Si vuelve a insistir una tercera vez</p>
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed italic" style="color: #b91c1c;">
        "I think the proper place for that conversation is in writing, with my representative copied."
      </p>
      <p class="text-xs mt-3" style="color: #991b1b;">
        Tres insistencias = está pescando información. Cierra firme. <strong>No tienes que defender la cifra</strong>; está enviada y sustentada en el expediente. El conciliator es neutral, ni la aprueba ni la rechaza, sólo la transmite.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!-- 4. LENGTH OF SERVICE                                          -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-6">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">4 · Tiempo en M&S</h2>
    <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="background: var(--color-cloud);">
      <p class="text-sm leading-relaxed" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">
        <em>"Thirteen years. I started in May 2013 and my employment ended on 3 May 2026."</em>
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============================================================ -->
  <!-- 5. REASONS GIVEN BY M&S                                       -->
  <!-- ============================================================ -->

  <section class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-6">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-4" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">5 · Las razones que dio M&S</h2>
    <div class="space-y-3">

      <div class="rounded-lg p-4" style="background: var(--color-cloud);">
        <p class="font-bold text-sm mb-1" style="color: var(--color-graphite);">Para el cambio de horario:</p>
        <p class="text-sm mb-3" style="color: var(--color-stone);">
          <em>"Operational requirements"</em> and <em>"the M&amp;S Way"</em>. M&amp;S did not provide any written justification or business case.
        </p>
        <div class="rounded p-3 mb-3" style="background: #f5f3ff; border-left: 3px solid #8b5cf6;">
          <p class="text-xs font-bold mb-1" style="color: #5b21b6;">↪ Contra-argumento (si quieres mencionarlo):</p>
          <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed" style="color: #4c1d95;">
            For more than two years before my resignation I was the only Visual Merchandiser in the store, working Monday to Friday with no weekend cover, and the store ran normally. Visual merchandising work cannot effectively be done on weekends because that is when customer footfall is highest and the store needs to focus on sales rather than on moving stock and displays. I was also never trained on tills.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded p-3 mb-3" style="background: #fef2f2; border-left: 3px solid #dc2626;">
          <p class="text-xs font-bold mb-1" style="color: #991b1b;">↪ El cambio no era una propuesta, era una imposición:</p>
          <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed" style="color: #b91c1c;">
            On 17 April, Mahnoor emailed me a "letter of enforcement" giving me four weeks' notice to comply with the new weekend pattern, and warning that failure to comply would lead to disciplinary action and ultimately dismissal. This made clear the change was being imposed under threat of dismissal, not negotiated.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded p-3 mb-3" style="background: #fffbeb; border-left: 3px solid #d97706;">
          <p class="text-xs font-bold mb-1" style="color: #92400e;">↪ Y no fueron sólo las dos reuniones formales:</p>
          <p class="text-xs leading-relaxed" style="color: #b45309;">
            Beyond the two formal meetings, my line manager approached me repeatedly in informal settings (VM Office, shop floor, before lunch break) asking for "a solution" and framing these as informal chats. I told her directly that this was causing me distress and asked her to schedule any further discussions on agreed days. The unscheduled approaches continued. I was also told she was due to go on holiday for two weeks and would hand my case to another manager, which added further uncertainty.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="rounded p-3" style="background: #fef2f2; border-left: 3px solid #dc2626;">
          <p class="text-xs font-bold mb-1" style="color: #991b1b;">↪ M&amp;S knew the reason from 16 April onwards (knowledge requirement):</p>
